Part 1

In this part you will explore the iris flower dataset that is built into R. You can use the command ?iris in R if you want to get some information about the dataset.

  • Copy the skeleton code (ListingÂ 1).
  • Look at FigureÂ 1 and relate the variables in the dataset to the figure. What is petal and sepal? What does width and length refer to? How are the measurements done? Try Googling for images if FigureÂ 1 is not enough.
  1. Compute the correlations between all numeric variables in the dataset. Save the result in a variable called correlations.
    • Are the correlations positive or negative? Does this make sense to you?
  2. Use ggplot to create a scatterplot with the sepal width on the x axis against the sepal length on the y axis. Save the resulting plot in a variable called plot1.
    • How does the plotted points match the correlations we computed before?
  3. Fit a linear regression model predicting the sepal length using sepal width. Save the model in a variable called model1.
    • Does the estimated coefficient for sepal width match what have seen in tasks 1 and 2?
  4. Compute the correlations between all numeric variables in the dataset using only the setosas. Save the result in a variable called correlations_setosa.
    • Are these correlations positive or negative? How are they different from the overall correlations? Does this make sense?
  5. Use ggplot to create a scatterplot with the sepal width on the x axis against the sepal length on the y axis. Color the points by flower species. Save the resulting plot in a variable called plot2
    • Does this match the correlations we computed for setosa flowers?
  6. Fit a linear regression model predicting the sepal length using sepal width and the flower species. Save the model is a variable called model2.
    • Does the estimated coefficient for Sepal.Width make sense? What happened when we added species to our model? How does it change the interpretation?
  7. Predict the sepal length of a setosa with a sepal width of 3.6 cm using your second model. Save the resulting prediction in a variable called prediction.
    • Does the prediction appear reasonable?

Part 2

In this part, we will look for important factors for predicting the onset of diabetes in Pima Indian women. Important: the dataset should be downloaded from Canvas and not from mlbench as in the lecture notes.

  • Download the Diabetes data from Canvas under Modules/Datasets/Diabetes data and store it in your working directory without renaming the file. This is important as the auto-corrector expects the code to search for the dataset in the working directory. Tip: If you donât know which is your current working directory, run getwd(). If you use setwd() in your code, please remove or comment this line before submitting to the autocorrector/Canvas.
  • Load the data and familiarize yourself with the dataset by performing EDA and reading about the variables on Canvas.
    • What predictors do you think will be relevant for the analysis? How is diabetes diagnosed and when is it measured with respect to the other variables in the dataset?
  1. Recode the variable Outcome as a factor (but do not recode any other variables).
  2. Fit a logistic regression model to predict the onset of diabetes. Save it as logistic_model
    • Use plots and descriptive statistics, predictor significance and AIC to find good predictors of diabetes.
    • Before fitting your model, impute missing values using mean imputation (overwrite the missing values for each variable with the variable average). Store the imputed data in a variable called imputed_data. Make sure you do your data exploration before imputation. Otherwise you will get biased results.
    • Use imputed_data to fit your model.
      • Make sure your all the predictors in your model have a statistically significant relationships with the outcome on a 5% significance level.
      • Test the performance of your model by computing the prediction accuracy on the whole dataset using a classification threshold of 50% (a predicted probability of above 50% predicts diabetes). If your model has a lower accuracy than 76.5%, find a better model. Save the prediction accuracy in a numeric variable called accuracy. Make sure your model is called logistic_model so the auto-corrector can find it.
    • Here we used the same data for fitting the regression model and evaluate the prediction accuracy of the fitted model. Reflect on why this may not always be a good idea. Do not use a train/test set when computing your accuracy since the auto-corrector will check your computation using the full dataset.

Make sure your R script runs from top to bottom after restarting R.
